==2003== William & Mary only played 10 games compared to the regular 11-game season due to a cancellation of the [[Maine Black Bears|Maine]] contest, which had been scheduled for September 27. The presidents of the Atlantic 10 Football Conference awarded the University of Maine a victory and the College of William & Mary a no-contest as a result of the cancellation of their game. The decision of the presidents, based upon the recommendation of the league's directors of athletics, was unprecedented in Atlantic 10 Football Conference history. Factored into the decision were Maine's efforts to play the game and the understanding of the unique circumstances facing William & Mary in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Isabel]]. However, the NCAA does not recognize the win in their official records. {{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2003 |Team= William & Mary Tribe |Image= WM Tribe logo.svg |ImageSize=80 |Conference= Atlantic 10 Conference |ShortConference= A-10 |Record= 5â5 |ConfRecord= 4â4 |HeadCoach= [[Jimmye Laycock]] (24th year) |OffCoach= [[Zbig Kepa]] (11th year) |DefCoach= [[Tom Clark (American football)|Tom Clark]] (3rd year) |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena= [[Zable Stadium]]&nbsp;(12,259 cap.) |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} {{CFB Schedule Start|time=|rank=|ranklink=no|rankyear=2003|tv=|attend=yes}} {{CFB Schedule Entry | date = September 5 | time = 7:00 pm | w/l = l | nonconf = yes | away = yes | neutral = | rank = | opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=Western Michigan Broncos|title=Western Michigan}} | opprank = | site_stadium = [[Waldo Stadium]] | site_cityst = [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo, MI]] | gamename = | score = 24â56 | overtime = | tv = | attend = 25,316 }} {{CFB Schedule Entry | date = September 13 | time = 1:00 pm | w/l = w | nonconf = yes | away = yes | neutral = | rank = | opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=VMI Keydets|title=Virginia Military Institute}} | opprank = | site_stadium = [[Alumni Memorial Field|Foster Stadium]] | sit